<br>
<!--EZCODE QUOTE START--><blockquote><strong><em>Quote:</em></strong><hr>There is one major problem with that system so. Lets say you make a 1,000:1 bet that the president dies on a certain day - and you win. You will have a very intense conversation with the FBI, DHS etc.<hr></blockquote><!--EZCODE QUOTE END--> <br>
<br>
Are you saying, Shamu, that someone should NOT be questioned if they are that accurate with their prediction?? If they're that accurate then they obviously have information on it, which makes em guilty in my eyes. The whole goal of this thing is to find out that information anyway.<br>
<br>
<!--EZCODE QUOTE START--><blockquote><strong><em>Quote:</em></strong><hr>I think the main problem is, encouraging people to bet money on the possibility of something as terrible as a terrorist attack is not moral.<hr></blockquote><!--EZCODE QUOTE END--><br>
<br>
But the actual terrorist action is moral, and should be allowed to happen? Exactly what other incentive would you give people to come forward with info--&quot;If you tell us what's going to happen, you'll get a cookie&quot;?? I don't think so. Yeah, we don't like to think that other human beings would be so immoral as to want money in exchange for saving someone's life, but its true whether we want to face it or not. What's wrong with putting that immorality to good use and possibly saving lives? <p>~~~~<br>
